The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, May 04, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, May 3: Liberalising the guidelines for acquisitions of foreign securities under the Esop scheme, the Reserve Bank today relaxed the condition of buying such securities at a concessional price. Under the existing norms, a resident individual, who is an employee or director of an Indian office or a branch of a foreign company in which the foreign holding is not less than 51 per cent, can acquire foreign securities under the Esop scheme, without any monetary limit, provided the Esop shares are offered at a concessional price. As a measure of further liberalisation, it has been decided to dispense with the condition that the shares should be offered at a concessional price, it said. 																								 New Delhi, May 3: IFC may invest more in private banks in India, including Kotak Mahindra Bank, although it has cut exposure in Centurion Bank and Global Trust Bank.																								 Mumbai, May 3: The board of Tata Power will meet on May 12 to consider a proposal of raising additional long-term resources.																								 Mumbai, May 3: Reliance Industries has increased the prices of some of its polyester products by 1 per cent to 3.9 per cent.																								 Calcutta, May 3: Dunlops net worth slipped to a negative Rs 491.40 crore as on March 31, 2004 from a negative Rs 460.79 crore in the previous fiscal.
